r>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Home Network.</span><hr size=1> I have one XP box and 2 win 98 box's. The name of my workgroup is Home.<br>
<br>
My father has an XP box and 1 win 98 box. The name of his workgroup is MSHome.<br>
<br>
If I want all my pc's to see eachother and I don't want his to have access to mine, what is the easiest route? We share a cable connection but he is about as computer illiterate as they come and I don't want him passing me the nice viruses that he seems to collect.<br>
<br>
Any input would be greatly appreciated.  <p><font color=green><b>Cendan Tankenpriest</b></font color><br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ukavissilversteel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>kavis Silversteel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 87<br> <font color=#E9D756>(12/31/01 4:32:38 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Home Network.</span><hr size=1> All you have to do is create the workgroup so that you can see each computer on the network but not share anything with him or do a password share where he has to have a password in order to save anything to your pc. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/utanuden.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tanuden</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 93<br> <font color=#E9D756>(12/31/01 5:32:58 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Some Ideas</span><hr size=1> I don't know how you share your internet connection, but you may want to invest in a Cable Router with an 8 port switch.  I had fits trying to get my XP box to see the internet through Win98 ICS.  Part of this might be due to AT&amp;T having trouble when I was configuring it, but now I have 2 XP boxes and 3 Win98SE boxes sharing the internet painlessly.  By using a router and not a computer as a gateway, you can set two different workgroups on the network and not worry about his workgroup having to share your workgroup for internet access.<br>
<br>
A second option might involve using different domains, but I don't know a lot about this subject, and I don't know if its possible with Win98SE and XP.<br>
<br>
Another option:<br>
Get the Cable router, and daisy chain two 4 port switches off of it...one for you, one for him.  Then configure the router to not allow traffic from your network ports to go to him, and vice versa. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ucendan.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cendan</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 410<br> <font color=#E9D756>(12/31/01 10:17:25 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Home Network.</span><hr size=1> I have a four port cable hub.  My 3 computers connect directly and then one line goes downstairs from my apartment to my fathers hub, which then splits to his 2 pc's.<br>
<br>
So the internet isn't a problem.  I just need to lock my pc's from him and vice versa.<br>
<br>
We are already in 2 different workgroups.<br>
<br>
Here is the problem.. in win 98 I would just set a password on the root share... but XP has inherited NT security which I know nothing about.<br>
<br>
The 2 win98 machines are already safe now (password share) but the problem remains with the XP box.  I need to know how to offer full access to my machines while blocking him.  Anyone know a good book on XP?<br>
<br>
<br>
Also, I plan on eventually turning my XP box into a server.  It has 2 hard drives and I have all the software... problem is I am JUST finding out about NTFS.  Should I go through the trouble of formatting now and going NTFS?<br>
<br>
I read somewhere about not being about to do a system recover in MS-DOS if I go 100% NTFS.  I read that I should partition and have my C root on a small FAT32 partition and have everything else on the NTFS partition... so... anyone that can validate or invalidate that info? <br>
<br>
Thanks. <p><font color=green><b>Cendan Tankenpriest</b></font color><br>
